PROJECT 5: AWS Security Compliance Dashboard
Date: Day 12
What I built:

Enabled AWS Config with full resource recording
Created S3 bucket for Config logs (dipesh-config-logs-2026)
Connected Config notifications to SNS security alerts
Added 3 AWS Config compliance rules:
s3-bucket-public-read-prohibited
iam-user-mfa-enabled
root-account-mfa-enabled
Deployed IAM compliance conformance pack (dipesh-iam-compliance)
Reviewed Security Hub executive dashboard
Verified complete security posture across all resources

Security concepts applied:

Continuous compliance monitoring with AWS Config
Automated rule checking for S3 public access
MFA enforcement verification for all IAM users
Root account MFA compliance checking
Conformance pack for IAM best practices
Centralized security findings in Security Hub
Real time SNS notifications for compliance changes

Challenges faced and resolved:

Received continuous SNS emails after enabling Config
Understood this is normal initial scan behavior
Emails reduced after initial resource scan completed
AWS Config integration not found in Security Hub catalog
Discovered integration is now built-in automatically
No manual configuration needed in updated AWS console
S3 bucket option not available in conformance pack setup
Newer AWS console handles storage automatically
Completed deployment without manual S3 configuration

Real world value:

AWS Config is mandatory for compliance frameworks like SOC2, PCI DSS and ISO27001
Conformance packs allow companies to deploy 50+ rules instantly
Security Hub gives single pane of glass for entire security posture
611 active findings shows real monitoring happening across 114 resources
This exact setup is used by enterprise security teams daily

Key learnings:

AWS Config records every configuration change in your account
Compliance rules automatically check resources against best practices
Conformance packs bundle multiple rules for specific compliance frameworks
Security Hub aggregates findings from Config, GuardDuty and other services
Initial Config scan generates many SNS notifications — expected behavior
AWS console updates mean some features work differently than documentation
Real security posture monitoring requires multiple services working together
